o London for a few days. Molly is excited about the idea because it means she will have some freedom from her stepmother. She imagines spending time with her father and enjoying simple meals without the strictness and formality that her stepmother imposes. Molly even fantasizes about riding a horse and feeling happy again after a long period of feeling old and joyless.\n","------\n","\n","\n","554\n","\"Molly, you're very glad to get rid of us, are not you?\"\"Not of you, Cynthia; at least, I don't think I am. Only, if you but knew how I love papa, and how I used to see a great deal more of him than I ever do now--\"\"Ah! I often think what interlopers we must seem, and are in fact--\"\"I don't feel you as such. You, at any rate, have been a new delight to me--a sister; and I never knew how charming such a relationship could be.\"\"But mamma?\" said Cynthia, half-suspiciously, half-sorrowfully.\"She is papa's wife,\" said Molly, quietly. \"I don't mean to say I'm not often very sorry to feel I'm no longer first with him; but it was\"--the violent colour flushed into her face till even her eyes burnt, and she suddenly found herself on the point of crying; the weeping ash-tree, the misery, the slow dropping comfort, and the comforter came all so vividly before her--\"it was Roger!\"--she went on looking up at Cynthia, as she overcame her slight hesitation at mentioning his name--\"Roger, who told me how I ought to take papa's marriage, when I was first startled and grieved at the news. Oh, Cynthia, what a great thing it is to be loved by him!\"\n","------\n","Molly is talking to Cynthia about her feelings towards her father and his new wife. Molly admits that she misses spending time with her father and feels like an outsider in their relationship. However, she expresses her love for her new sister, Cynthia, and how she has brought joy into her life. Cynthia is concerned about Molly's feelings towards their mother, but Molly reassures her that she understands her fath