e the rest of the family were at dinner--after Molly's tea and hour of quiet repose, Parkes came and dressed her in some of the new clothes prepared for the Kirkpatrick visit, and did her hair in some new and pretty way, so that when Molly looked at herself in the cheval-glass, she scarcely knew the elegant reflection to be that of herself. She was fetched down by Lady Harriet into the great long formidable drawing-room, which as an interminable place of pacing, had haunted her dreams ever since her childhood. At the further end sat Lady Cumnor at her tapestry work; the light of fire and candle seemed all concentrated on that one bright part where presently Lady Harriet made tea, and Lord Cumnor went to sleep, and Sir Charles read passages aloud from the _Edinburgh Review_ to the three ladies at their work.\n","------\n","Sir Charles takes Molly under his protection and speaks to her in a friendly and sympathetic manner. Later, Molly is dressed in new clothes and her hair is styled differently. She is then brought into a large drawing-room where Lady Cumnor is working on tapestry. Lady Harriet makes tea, Lord Cumnor falls asleep, and Sir Charles reads aloud from the Edinburgh Review to the three ladies.\n","------\n","\n","\n","791\n","When Molly went to bed she was constrained to admit that staying at the Towers as a visitor was rather pleasant than otherwise; and she tried to reconcile old impressions with new ones, until she fell asleep. There was another comparatively quiet day before the expected guests began to arrive in the evening. Lady Harriet took Molly a drive in her little pony-carriage; and for the first time for many weeks Molly began to feel the delightful spring of returning health; the dance of youthful spirits in the fresh air cleared by the previous day's rain.\n","------\n","Molly is staying at the Towers as a visitor and finds it pleasant. She tries to reconcile her old impressions with the new ones before falling asleep. The next day, Molly goe